**Clinical Reasoning:**
In disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), there is widespread consumption of clotting factors leading to impaired coagulation. Tests like activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT) often prolong due to deficiency of factors involved in intrinsic pathway. D-dimer levels rise significantly because of extensive fibrin degradation products. Clot solubility decreases since clots become unstable and break apart easily. Prothrombin time (PT) may also be affected, though less consistently than APTT. However, among the listed tests, prothrombin level itself—referring to circulating prothrombin—is not typically assessed nor expected to be abnormal in DIC; rather, PT reflects its function. Thus, prothrombin concentration isn't reliably altered compared to other markers like APTT, D-dimers, or clot solubility.

